SIMPLE: salute
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Salute
<hw>Sa*lute"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Saluted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Saluting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>salutare</ets>,
<ets>salutatum</ets>, from <ets>salus</ets>, <ets>-utis</ets>, health,
safety. See <er>Salubrious</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To address, as
with expressions of kind wishes and courtesy; to greet; to
hail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>salute</qex> you with this kingly title.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, to give a sign of good will; to compliment by
an act or ceremony, as a kiss, a bow, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You have the prettiest tip of a finger . . . I must take the
freedom to <qex>salute</qex> it.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mil. & Naval)</fld> <def>To honor, as some day,
person, or nation, by a discharge of cannon or small arms, by dipping
colors, by cheers, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To promote the welfare and safety of; to benefit; to
gratify.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧If this <xex>salute</xex> my
blood a jot.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Salute</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Salute
<hw>Sa*lute"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>salut</ets>. See <er>Salute</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of saluting, or expressing kind wishes or respect;
salutation; greeting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sign, token, or ceremony, expressing good will,
compliment, or respect, as a kiss, a bow, etc.</def>
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mil. & Naval)</fld> <def>A token of respect or
honor for some distinguished or official personage, for a foreign vessel
or flag, or for some festival or event, as by presenting arms, by a
discharge of cannon, volleys of small arms, dipping the colors or the
topsails, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Saluter</ent>⟦br⟧
